      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "IMRC's operational strength lies in its ability to maintain high liquidity and financial stability. The organization holds <cite id=\"16\">55.7 months of working capital</cite> in working capital, providing a massive safety net for long-term projects. This financial health is paired with a clear <cite id=\"17\">theory of change</cite> focused on alleviating poverty through awareness and direct aid. Their multi-sectoral approach is evidenced by their 2019 metrics, where they <cite id=\"18\">benefited 21,039 students</cite> while simultaneously managing large-scale food programs that distributed <cite id=\"19\">7.5 million grains of meals</cite>."
      ],
      "summary": "Indian Muslim Relief and Charities (IMRC) is a humanitarian organization dedicated to helping <cite id=\"1\">India's Muslims and minorities achieve security, freedom, and equality</cite>. Founded in <cite id=\"2\">1981</cite>, the organization has spent over four decades building a robust infrastructure for <cite id=\"3\">direct service delivery across India</cite>, specifically targeting the state of Jammu and Kashmir and other marginalized regions. In 2023, IMRC reported <cite id=\"4\">total revenue of $13,833,809</cite>, primarily driven by <cite id=\"5\">$13.39 million in public contributions</cite>. The organization maintains a <cite id=\"6\">program expense ratio of 89.8%</cite>, directing the majority of its resources toward critical interventions in education, healthcare, and emergency relief. Their impact is significant; for instance, in 2021 alone, they <cite id=\"7\">treated 183,100 patients</cite> and <cite id=\"8\">provided 7.2 million meals</cite> to those in need. IMRC is a <cite id=\"9\">zakat-eligible entity</cite> that serves the asnaf categories of <cite id=\"10\">fuqara (the poor) and masakin (the needy)</cite>, making it a primary vehicle for American Muslim donors seeking to support core humanitarian needs in India.",
